05006nam a22007935i 9780231530873DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2012    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315308737 a10.7312/rowl158542doi  a(DE-B1597)459283  a(OCoLC)979969537  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDS872.N35 .R68 2013 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a952.0250921 aRowley, G., eauthor.13aAn Imperial Concubine's Tale :bScandal, Shipwreck, and Salvation in Seventeenth-Century Japan /cG. Rowley. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource :b11 color illus, 3 maps, 1 chart  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. A Courtier's Life, in and out of the World -- tChapter 2. The Year 1600: A World Again at War -- tChapter 3. At the Court of the Dragon -- tChapter 4. Scandal -- tChapter 5. The Tale of Kazan -- tChapter 6. Shipwreck -- tChapter 7. The Long Reprieve -- tChapter 8 Salvation -- tEpilogue -- tPrincipal Characters -- tGlossary -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJapan in the early seventeenth century was a wild place. Serial killers stalked the streets of Kyoto at night, while noblemen and women mingled freely at the imperial palace, drinking saké and watching kabuki dancing in the presence of the emperor's principal consort. Among these noblewomen was an imperial concubine named Nakanoin Nakako, who in 1609 became embroiled in a sex scandal involving both courtiers and young women in the emperor's service. As punishment, Nakako was banished to an island in the Pacific Ocean, but she never reached her destination. Instead, she was shipwrecked and spent fourteen years in a remote village on the Izu Peninsula before she was finally allowed to return to Kyoto. In 1641, Nakako began a new adventure: she entered a convent and became a Buddhist nun.Recounting the remarkable story of this resilient woman and her war-torn world, G. G. Rowley investigates aristocratic family archives, village storehouses, and the records of imperial convents. She follows the banished concubine as she endures rural exile, receives an unexpected reprieve, and rediscovers herself as the abbess of a nunnery. While unraveling Nakako's unusual tale, Rowley also reveals the little-known lives of samurai women who sacrificed themselves on the fringes of the great battles that brought an end to more than a century of civil war. Written with keen insight and genuine affection, An Imperial Concubine's Tale tells the true story of a woman's extraordinary life in seventeenth-century Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aBuddhist nunszJapanvBiography. 0aConcubinagezJapanxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/rowl15854423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231530873.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKA